g.text: An ORANGE transition is always followed by a YELLOW transition and vice-versa.
Pengine processing or idling is done while the machine is in one of the states.
Better labels for the states would be:
ORANGE transitions are performed based on messages/requests coming from the Pengine client.
--- All the messages here are depicted as synchronous.
--- However, there are also asynchronous messages like "abort" to kick the machine out
of state 3 - so this diagram is missing a few elements.
YELLOW transitions correspond to messages/responses going to the Pengine client.
--- Synchronously: as direct response to previous Pengine Client requests;
--- "Sort of asynchronously": all the transitions exiting state "3" are based on processing
conditions encountered while running the goal submitted via an "ask" message,.
AFAIK, this machine is independent of the HTTP session state.
You can close the HTTP session, and reconnect later using a previously obtained Pengine Id.
.... But are messages in the queue delivered at that point? We need to test!
Missing is the timeout event whcih tears down a Pengine after 3 minutes of idling.
Note that all the messages are HTTP messages, which may have their own internal chunking for large
data blocks. (What happens if there is an error in the HTTP protocol?)
- Websockets or HTTP/2 woule be more flexible for such a back-and-forth than HTTP/1.1
